Math 104 - Section 5 - Introduction to Analysis
Instructor: Shamgar Gurevich
Lectures: TuTh 3:30-5:00pm, Room 71 Evans
Course Control Number: 54799
Office: 867 Evans
Office Hours: TuTh 5:00-6:00pm
Prerequisites:  
Required Text: Walter Rudin, Principles of Mathematical Analysis
Recommended Reading: 
Syllabus: Real and complex numbers, basic topology, sequences and series, continuity, differentiation, integration, sequences and series of functions, linear algebra, Fourier series and integrals.
Course Webpage: http://math.berkeley.edu/~shamgar/104F07.html
Grading: There will be weekly assignments which will be due in one week, a midterm exam and a final. They will count toward the grade as follows:
 
Assignments 30% 
Midterm 30% 
Final 40%
Attitude: In our course we will study some basics of analysis. The attitude will be to help you to develop your way on how to think about some mathematical objects that you will encounter during your undergraduate studies. Moreover, I expect you to be an integral part of the course, i.e., to attend lectures, to participate in the discussions, to submit homework, and to visit me during my office hours. 
What: We intend to cover all the basic material so we can understand why a nice function on the circle can be written as a linear combination of exponential functions en(x) = e2&#960;inx, n &#8712; Z.  In particular I hope to formulate, explain and prove the Stone-Weierstrass theorem.



